---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { site, href, KIND_LABEL } from '../site';
import { parseStats } from '../lib/schema';
import rawStats from '../data/stats.json';

const stats = parseStats(rawStats);
const n = (x: number) => x.toLocaleString('en-US');

/* Rounded for running prose (style rule 41); exact counts live on /coverage/.
   Falls back to the exact figure below 100 so a thin ledger never
   renders "about 0". */
const approx = (x: number) => (x < 100 ? n(x) : n(Math.round(x / 100) * 100));

/* One live ratio argues subtraction better than two lifetime totals. Floored at
   2 so a fresh ledger never renders "one cluster in 0". */
const oneIn = n(
  Math.max(2, Math.round(stats.pipeline.clusters_total / Math.max(1, stats.pipeline.curations_done)))
);

/* The ledger's own freshness date, formatted for prose (style rule 44) and
   pinned to UTC so the stamp reads the same wherever the site is built. */
const asOf = new Date(stats.generated_at).toLocaleDateString('en-US', {
  month: 'long',
  day: 'numeric',
  year: 'numeric',
  timeZone: 'UTC',
});

/** 'claude-haiku-4-5' -> 'Claude Haiku 4.5' (style rule 63), rendered from
    pipeline config so the prose tracks the live stages. Drops a trailing
    YYYYMMDD snapshot suffix if one is ever pinned. */
const modelName = (id: string) => {
  const parts = id.replace(/-\d{8}$/, '').split('-');
  const words = parts
    .filter((p) => !/^\d+$/.test(p))
    .map((p) => p.charAt(0).toUpperCase() + p.slice(1));
  const version = parts.filter((p) => /^\d+$/.test(p)).join('.');
  return version ? `${words.join(' ')} ${version}` : words.join(' ');
};
---
<Base
  title={`About | ${site.name}`}
  description={`${site.name} reads the firehose of technology, AI, and science, then keeps the handful of stories that matter. How the pipeline works, what earns a slot, and what it costs the reader (nothing).`}
  compactHeader
>
  <article class="article measure measure--center">
    <header class="article__head">
      <span class="label">About</span>
      <h1 class="article__title">Read everything. Keep almost nothing.</h1>
      <p class="article__standfirst">What the machine reads, how it ranks and cuts, and how to check it against its own ledger.</p>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>There is too much to read, and most of it isn’t worth reading. {site.name} reads it anyway. It watches the places technology, AI, and the sciences break first (the labs, the front pages, the long tail of practitioner blogs) and files the few stories that matter, each with a plain account of why. About one cluster in {oneIn} survives to become a pick. The cuts are the product.</p>

      <h2 id="how-it-works">How it works</h2>
      <p>Everything starts wide. The pipeline pulls from about {approx(stats.sources.verified)} verified sources: RSS feeds plus Hacker News, Lobsters, Reddit, arXiv, Mastodon trends, Google News, Wikipedia current events, and GDELT. Items are canonicalized and clustered, so one story reported on a dozen surfaces counts once. A deterministic score then ranks each cluster on consensus, engagement, reputation, recency, and topic fit. No model has touched anything yet.</p>
      <p>Then three do, in rising order of cost. {modelName(stats.models.triage)} triages the ranked clusters down to finalists. {modelName(stats.models.deep)} reads each finalist in full, pulls the load-bearing details, and writes the one line that says whether to care. {modelName(stats.models.digest)} writes the editions, under a style guide with no appeals process. Those names come from the pipeline’s own configuration; when a stage changes models, this paragraph changes with it.</p>
      <p>The editions run on a fixed clock: the {KIND_LABEL.daily.toLowerCase()} on weekday mornings, the {KIND_LABEL.weekly.toLowerCase()} on Fridays, then the {KIND_LABEL.monthly.toLowerCase()}, the {KIND_LABEL.quarterly.toLowerCase()}, and {KIND_LABEL.yearly.toLowerCase()}. Each cadence answers its own question. The daily says what happened; the weekly names the through-lines; the retrospectives weigh what proved to matter.</p>
      <p>The pipeline writes what it publishes into <a href={site.repoUrl}>this site’s repository</a> and pushes; GitHub Actions builds and deploys the result. The site is static. If the machine stops, the site stands; it stops getting newer.</p>

      <h2>What earns a slot</h2>
      <p>Every edition is written for one reader: a senior engineer who wants primary sources, technical depth, and no theater. A story earns a slot on consequence (it changes what a practitioner builds, ships, secures, buys, or believes), on novelty, on evidence, or on durability, and it ranks by how many of those it clears and how hard. By policy, a day narrows to about 150 finalists; an edition keeps a handful.</p>
      <p>The cuts are by standing rule: marketing dressed as news, point-release churn, engagement bait, vendor benchmarks without methodology, and thin rewrites of someone else’s reporting. When unsure, cut.</p>
      <p>What survives is handled by rule. Claims stay attributed claims until independently checked; preprints are labeled; self-reported benchmarks are flagged every time. Where credible sources disagree, both run, with names attached. The primary source is linked first, always. When the original sits behind a paywall, a free read is linked beside it.</p>

      <h2>Why trust it</h2>
      <p>A publication written by machine earns trust the way an instrument does: by being checkable. Do not trust it. Check it. The <a href={href('/coverage/')}>coverage page</a> shows what gets read, which surfaces are loudest, and the pipeline’s numbers, down to which model ran each stage; the <a href={href('/sources/')}>sources page</a> names every feed on the roll. The figures here (the source count, the survival ratio, the model behind each stage) are read from that same ledger, regenerated at each publish, most recently on {asOf}.</p>

      <h2 id="open-source">Open source</h2>
      <p>The machine that writes the ledger is itself open. Every part of it (the fetchers, the deterministic score, the prompts, the rubric that cuts, and the code that renders this page) lives in <a href={site.repoUrl}>one public repository</a> under the MIT license. Read it, run it, fork it, or lift a piece for your own. The claims on this page (no tracking, a fixed clock, these models at these stages) are not requests for trust; they are lines you can go and find. A publication you cannot inspect is just a louder opinion. This one you can inspect, and it stays that way.</p>

      <h2>What it costs</h2>
      <p>Nothing, in money or in data. There is no account, no tracking, and no analytics: the site does not measure attention, so it has nothing to sell. <a href={href('/preferences/')}>Reading preferences</a> (theme, type size, density, muted sections, the signals panel) are stored in this browser’s localStorage and nowhere else; nothing about a visit leaves the device. Close the tab and the relationship ends.</p>

      <h2>Subscribe</h2>
      <p>{site.name} is built to live in a feed reader. Point one at <a href={href('/rss.xml')}>the full feed</a>, take <a href={href('/digests/rss.xml')}>the digests alone</a>, or pick a single cadence or section from <a href={href('/feeds/')}>the feed directory</a>. Picks arrive as they’re curated; editions arrive on their clock. Every edition published stays in <a href={href('/archive/')}>the archive</a>.</p>

      <h2>Colophon</h2>
      <p>Schibsted Grotesk sets the headlines, Source Serif 4 the body, IBM Plex Mono the furniture; all three are self-hosted. No images anywhere, only type, spacing, and hairline rules. Astro 5 builds the site; GitHub Pages serves it. The site and the pipeline behind it are open source, MIT licensed.</p>
      <p>{site.name} is built and run by one person, <a href={site.authorUrl}>{site.author}</a>. Corrections, broken links, and bad calls go through the <a href={href('/contact/')}>contact page</a>. The words are machine-written; the responsibility is not.</p>
    </div>
    <a class="back" href={href('/')}>← Front page</a>
  </article>
</Base>
